{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Cicero played an outsized and underappreciated role in the development of the German Enlightenment -or so we argue in this chapter.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The case for Cicero ' s importance in this period of intellectual history is more difficult to establish than its Anglophone counterpart.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "One reason for this is that the Enlightenment in Germany took a different form than it did in the English-speaking world.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "In Germany, on the other hand, the Enlightenment, at least initially, was propelled mainly by university-based philosophers -largely in the Wolffian tradition.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "However, direct references to or discussions of Cicero and his works are generally absent in this era of German school philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "That Cicero played a vital role for the representatives of so-called ' popular philosophy ' has already been suggested by some scholars.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Focusing on a central theme in German philosophy in the second half of the eighteenth century -the human vocation ( Bestimmung des Menschen ) -we illustrate in concrete terms the monumental influence Cicero had on the trajectory of the German Enlightenment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The impact of Christian Wolff ' s philosophy on the development of the German Enlightenment can hardly be overstated.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Popular philosophy as a philosophical movement in Germany is notoriously elusive, in part because its defining feature is its distance from systematic philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Above all else, popular philosophy placed knowledge on the foundation of ' common sense ' or ' sound reason. '",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "In this context, a theme later sloganized as the ' human vocation ' ( Bestimmung des Menschen ) gained particular importance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The importance of this topic for this period of intellectual history is undisputed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Its historical roots, however, are less clear.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "While its connection to antiquity is obvious -not least because of Spalding ' s direct references -scholars have so far tended to make vague references to Stoic influence.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "In the next section, we examine this presumed Stoic origin while also giving serious consideration to Spalding ' s explicit reference to Cicero ' s De legibus.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "In so doing we aim to demonstrate that Cicero provided an impetus and stimulus for Spalding ' s own reflections on the human vocation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "By extension, Cicero also played a crucial role in the development of German philosophy in the second half of the eighteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "As mentioned above, the only three authors Spalding explicitly refers to in the first edition of his text all hail from the ancient Roman world: Horace, Persius, and Cicero.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "One connection between this otherwise unlikely trio stands out: each of the three is connected in a prominent way with a Hellenistic philosophical school.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "It is particularly noteworthy that Spalding ' s essay mirrors the ring composition of this passage from Cicero: introspection and self-knowledge are ultimately connected, after a series of stages, with awareness of cosmic order and divine providence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Christian Garve was one of the most influential philosophers in Germany in the second half of the eighteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Garve, who was also in close contact with Spalding, pursued a project making the philosophical ideas of the Enlightenment accessible to a wider audience in a popularizing form.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "In pursuit of this end Garve translated and commented in detail on well-known and esteemed works of philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "It has been known for some time that Cicero was an important model for the popular philosophy movement, which exerted considerable influence on the development of German philosophy in the second half of the eighteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "The exact nature of this influence, however, has up to this point remained obscure.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "In this chapter we have shown in concrete terms how Cicero ' s legacy is reflected in two prominent popular philosophers and in a central question of the time, namely the question of the human vocation.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
